<DOC><DOCNO> AP891126-0015 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-89 1130EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     11-26 0385</FIRST><SECOND>AM-South Korea,0395</SECOND><HEAD>Police Storm Campus To Block Anti-Government Protest</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD><BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hundreds of riot police firing teargas stormed a college campus Sunday to block a rally by radicalstudents and workers seeking the overthrow of President RohTae-woo. They arrested about 500 protesters.   Police blocked minor protests at three colleges in the southerncities of Pusan, Masan and Taegu, officials said. Students foughtpolice with firebombs and rocks after being blocked from marchingoff the campuses, they said.   Riot troopers in green combat fatigues and black visored helmetsstormed the campus of Yonsei University in Seoul just beforeprotesters were to start a rally organized by five radical groups.About 2,000 troopers were deployed around the campus to block thedemonstration.   They chased students across the campus, tearing down posters andsmashing loudspeakers, chairs and the podium for the rally. Policebanned the rally as a threat to public order, but 1,200 peopleturned out anyway.   Hundreds of masked students armed with firebombs and clubsbattled police for several hours after the troops attacked. Policearmored vans with tear gas launchers fired barrages of tear gasbombs to drive protesters back.   ``Let's unite to terminate the Roh Tae-woo regime!'' protestersshouted.   Police officials, who refused to be named, said about 500protesters were arrested in Seoul, most as they headed to therally. The officials said most of the detainees would be releasedafter being questioned.   Officers were seen beating and slapping a number of studentsseized during fighting at Yonsei. Police said they had no word oninjuries.   Hundreds of riot police guarded key government buildings indowntown Seoul to prevent possible attacks by radicals. More than200 ringed the U.S. Embassy.   Radical groups had called for protests in an effort to revivetheir flagging movement to topple the conservative government. Butthe radicals lack public support because of their extremist viewsand violent tactics.   Radical groups want to overthrow the government and create a``workers and farmers state.'' They also want immediatereunification with Communist North Korea.   The anti-American radicals also demand an end to close ties withWashington and the expulsion of the 43,000 U.S. troops based inSouth Korea under a mutual defense treaty against North Korea.</TEXT></DOC>